It&#39;s possible to convert this loop to a stream. You just need some intermediate object to hold the object and its&#39; score. Record is perfect for this job:
```
public record MyObjWrapper(MyObj myObj, double score) {
}
```
Now calculate the score and [map][1] each object and score to the wrapper, find the [max][2] element by providing appropriate comparator and extract `MyObj` from the wrapper.
```
public MyObj determineMyObjForDataStream(String data) {
  List&lt;MyObj&gt; myObjs = myRepository.findAll();
  List&lt;String&gt; splitData = Arrays.stream(data.split(BLANK_SPACE_STRING))
          .map(String::toLowerCase)
          .toList();
  return myObjs.stream()
          .map(obj -&gt; {
            long hits = obj.keywords().stream()
                    .map(String::toLowerCase)
                    .filter(splitData::contains)
                    .count();
            double currentScore = hits / (double) splitData.size();
            return new MyObjWrapper(obj, currentScore);
          })
          .max(Comparator.comparing(MyObjWrapper::score))
          .map(MyObjWrapper::myObj)
          .orElse(null);
}
```
Additionally, i would change `splitData` to a `Set` (contains is more efficient for set), unless you have a reason not to use set (maybe you need those duplicates when getting the size?).

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#map-java.util.function.Function-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#max-java.util.Comparator-

